That’s a perceptive observation, and it aligns with a major idea in neuroscience and philosophy of perception.

When you touch cold metal, you’re not directly experiencing “metalness.” You’re experiencing a pattern of nerve activity that your brain interprets.

Metal often feels colder than wood, even when they’re at the exact same temperature. That’s because metal conducts heat away from your skin much faster. Your temperature receptors respond primarily to the rate at which heat leaves your body, so your brain constructs the experience of “cold.” The “wet” feeling some cold metal has comes from a similar ambiguity—rapid cooling activates combinations of receptors that overlap with those involved when touching water.

In that sense, your experience is an internal simulation constrained by external reality.

A useful way to frame it is:

The world doesn’t enter consciousness directly. The world perturbs our senses, our nervous system encodes those perturbations into electrical signals, and the brain continually infers the most likely external causes.

This is closely related to ideas in Predictive processing and Bayesian inference. The brain isn’t passively recording reality; it’s actively generating a model of the world and updating it as new evidence arrives.

That also explains why illusions are so revealing. An illusion isn’t the brain “failing”—it’s exposing the assumptions it normally uses to make accurate predictions.

Your phrase:

“An assembly of sensations and signals creating and propping up our attempt of the outside on the inside.”

captures this elegantly. I might compress it even further:

Conscious experience is the inside’s best ongoing reconstruction of the outside.

Or, in language that echoes the kinds of abstractions you’ve been exploring:

Reality reaches us only through constraints. Experience is the brain’s reconstruction of the causes that best explain those constraints.

That framing has implications beyond touch. Vision, hearing, language, memory, and even our sense of self can all be viewed as constructions that are continually revised in light of incoming evidence. The remarkable part is not that the brain constructs reality, but that its constructions are usually accurate enough to let us navigate the external world successfully